esented through a strong **interactive UI / analysis layer**.\ndocs/milestones.md:17:- **Programming-heavy** \\= data plumbing, APIs, asset pipelines, engine implementation, scene generation, UI, orchestration, reproducibility  \ndocs/milestones.md:32:- **Jack** owns infrastructure, tooling, engine wiring, scene system, UI, and experiment automation  \ndocs/milestones.md:33:- **Grant** owns the wave model, discretization choices, coupling assumptions, stability reasoning, and validation logic  \ndocs/milestones.md:38:  - synapse coupling API  \ndocs/milestones.md:54:- scene generator  \ndocs/milestones.md:65:- define operators and coupling  \ndocs/milestones.md:75:- choose the circuit  \ndocs/milestones.md:88:| 2 | Lock the circuit boundary | Shared leaning programming (65/35) | Jack lead, Grant supports | Active visual subset and context graph |\ndocs/milestones.md:90:| 4 | Turn subset selection into a proper tool | Programming-heavy (80/20) | Jack lead | Reproducible named subsets |\ndocs/milestones.md:93:| 7 | Map synapses and define inter-neuron coupling | Shared leaning math-physics (45/55) | Shared lead | Patch-level coupling model |\ndocs/milestones.md:94:| 8 | Build the visual input stack | Split by submodule | Split | Stimuli, retinal mapping, scene generator |\ndocs/milestones.md:100:| 14 | Build the UI and analysis dashboard | Programming-heavy (90/10) | Jack lead | Polished demo and interactive inspection |\ndocs/milestones.md:103:| 17 | Extend to whole-brain context views | Programming-heavy (75/25) | Jack lead | Context graph around the active visual circuit |\ndocs/milestones.md:119:**Morphology-resolved surface dynamics constitute an additional intraneuronal computational degree of freedom, capable of shaping circuit input-output transformations through distributed spatiotemporal state on neuronal structure.**\ndocs/milestones.md:123:**In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.**\ndocs/milestones.md:145:* **`P0`**: canonical point baseline using passive leaky linear non-spiking single-compartment neurons matched to the same circuit and readout  \ndocs/milestones.md:151: In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\ndocs/milestones.md:160: The same stimulus driving the same circuit in two models, producing a small but real output difference that shrinks or disappears when geometry is shuffled.\ndocs/milestones.md:179:2. **`10–25 s`**: split screen with matched point baseline on the left and surface model on the right for the same T4/T5-centered circuit  \ndocs/milestones.md:182:5. **`50–60 s`**: freeze on a summary panel captioned **“Small, causal, geometry-dependent computational effect.”**\ndocs/milestones.md:186:* stimulus overview for the simple moving-edge input  \ndocs/milestones.md:188:* shared output trace overlay for the same circuit and stimulus  \ndocs/milestones.md:193:* final milestone decision panel summarizing the four decision-rule checks\ndocs/milestones.md:199:* naturalistic cinematic scenes  \ndocs/milestones.md:251:## **Milestone 2 — Lock the circuit boundary**\ndocs/milestones.md:258:Choose and freeze the smallest scientifically defensible circuit boundary for the first real simulation pass.\ndocs/milestones.md:260:### **Locked circuit decision**\ndocs/milestones.md:271:Only the columns inside the selected stimulus footprint should be included, plus a **one-ring halo** so each active detector retains its local sampling neighborhood.\ndocs/milestones.md:303:* LPi/LPTC inventory or wide-field tangential-cell circuitry  \ndocs/milestones.md:318:Promote additional circuitry only when i